#. (itstool) path: sect2/para
#: xml/tuning_systemresources.xml:377
msgid "The <command>ionice</command> command lets you prioritize disk access for single processes. This enables you to give less I/O priority to background processes with heavy disk access that are not time-critical, such as backup jobs. <command>ionice</command> also lets you raise the I/O priority for a specific process to make sure this process always has immediate access to the disk. The caveat of this feature is that standard writes are cached in the page cache and are written back to persistent storage only later by an independent kernel process. Thus the I/O priority setting generally does not apply for these writes. Also be aware that I/O class and priority setting is obeyed only by <emphasis>CFQ</emphasis> I/O scheduler (refer to <xref linkend=\"cha.tuning.io.schedulers\"/>). You can set the following three scheduling classes:"
